README — Recent Code Updates (Microstructure Handling & Output Changes)

This note summarizes ONLY the recent modifications made to the code. All
physics, model formulation, and simulation workflow remain unchanged.

  ------------------------------------
  1. Multiple Microstructure Support
  ------------------------------------

Previously: - Grain structure was read only once from:
inputs/gchar_poly.txt inputs/gnumb_poly.txt inputs/gdata_poly.bin

Now: - Multiple microstructures can be used sequentially: inputs/struc1/
inputs/struc2/ inputs/struc3/ …

Each structure directory must contain: gchar_poly.txt and gdata_poly.bin

gnumb_poly.txt is required inside "inputs" as number of grains DO NOT change.

Execution behavior: 
Structure 1 → all parameter sets 
Structure 2 → all parameter sets 
Structure 3 → all parameter sets

The code loads one structure, runs all simulations, then moves to the
next structure.

  ----------------------------------
  2. Output Directory Organization
  ----------------------------------

Sweep text files are now written per structure:

output/struc001/ sweep001.txt sweep002.txt 
      struc002/ sweep001.txt

No intermediate simXXX folder for sweep files anymore.

  -------------------------------------
  3. Binary Field Output Organization
  -------------------------------------

To avoid clutter from many field dumps, binary outputs are stored as:

output/ struc001/ fields/ sim001/ Pm_xxxxxx.bin Ps_xxxxxx.bin sim002/

This keeps sweep text files clean while grouping field dumps by
simulation.

  ----------------------------------
  4. Reduced Binary Dump Frequency
  ----------------------------------

Previously: - Field dumps occurred at every output step (~85 per sweep).

Now: - Dumps are reduced using a stride-based sampling. - Roughly ~20
dumps per sweep (not exact).

Implementation: - A separate output-row counter is used instead of
timestep count. - Dumps occur approximately every few sweep rows.

  -----------------------
  5. Safe Path Handling
  -----------------------

All path formatting now uses safe_snprintf() instead of sprintf().

Purpose: - Prevent buffer overflow - Avoid truncated filenames - Improve
robustness for long paths

  ---------------------------------
  6. Automatic Directory Creation
  ---------------------------------

Directories are automatically created using:

    make_dir_p(path)

No manual folder setup is required.

  -------------------------------------
  7. No Changes To Simulation Physics
  -------------------------------------

The following remain unchanged:

-   Phase-field formulation
-   TDGL evolution scheme
-   Electrostatics / vacancy transport
-   Input parameter format
-   Parameter calibration
-   Sweep data structure

  ---------
  Summary
  ---------

Key improvements:

1.  Sequential multi-microstructure simulation capability.
2.  Cleaner output directory organization.
3.  Reduced number of binary field dumps.
4.  Safer file handling.

No changes to model physics.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
8. Generating Microstructures and Populating inputs/struc*/ Directories
---------------------------------------------------------------------

Microstructures are generated using the separate generator code:
    genpolycr_layered

To generate single-layer (1L) structures in the format expected by the
modified simulation code:

1) Open the generator source (genpolycr_layered) and set:
       int layer_counts[]  = {10};
       int n_layers        = 1;

2) Compile the generator.

3) Run the generator once to create ONE microstructure. It will produce:
       gchar.txt
       gnumb.txt
       gdata.bin

4) Rename the outputs to the expected polycrystal names:
       gchar_poly.txt
       gnumb_poly.txt
       gdata_poly.bin

5) Create a structure directory and place the renamed files inside it:
       inputs/struc1/
           gchar_poly.txt
           gdata_poly.bin

6) Repeat steps (3)–(5) to create additional structures:
       inputs/struc2/
       inputs/struc3/
       ...
   Each run of the generator produces one independent microstructure.
   For each new structure, re-run the generator and copy/rename outputs
   into the next inputs/struc* directory.

Notes:
- ng_total is constant across structures (same grain count file format).
- Only “compile + run” is needed repeatedly to generate many structures,
  then organize them into inputs/struc* directories as shown above.

